    "title": "D.R.A.K.K.E.N.",
    "description": "Tokyo, 2198. You came to Akihabara for an anime convention. You woke up in an alley with your organs harvested and a classified military prototype fused to your chest cavity — one that's slowly turning you into a chrome-scaled dragon. You have 90 days before the trial license expires and the system keeping you alive shuts down. A megacorp CEO wants to own you. A hacktivist in a coffee shop wants to save you. The clock is ticking, and the only heart you have left keeps asking for a license key you don't have.",
    "background": "You saved for three years. Three years of meal-prepped soy paste and recycled air in your New York micro-unit, three years of overtime at the data-entry farm, three years of telling yourself it would be worth it — because Akihabara was calling.\n\nCathrin Kardashev. Twenty-six. Middle class by the thinnest of margins, which in 2198 means you still get to dream. And your dream was NeoTokyo AnimeFest, the largest convention on Earth, a cathedral of light and sound in the electric heart of a city that never learned how to sleep.\n\nYou made it. You walked the neon corridors. You bought a limited-edition figurine with money you couldn't afford to spend.\n\nThen, on the second night, walking back to your capsule hotel through a side street just two blocks from the main strip, something stung your neck. The world tilted. Hands caught you before you hit the ground — not to save you, but to carry you.\n\nOrgan harvesters. Black market chop shops that strip tourists like cars in a junkyard. They took your kidneys, your liver, one lung, your spleen, and your heart. They replaced nothing. They dumped what was left of you in a dumpster behind a ramen joint, along with a fist-sized lump of chrome and wire that kept demanding a license key they couldn't crack.\n\nThat lump was D.R.A.K.K.E.N. — the Draconic Reconstructive Adaptive Kinetic-Kill Enhancement Network. A classified AgroDyne military prototype, intercepted from a dead corporate runner who'd been harvested the same night you were. The harvesters couldn't sell it. Couldn't use it. So they threw it away with the rest of the garbage.\n\nBut D.R.A.K.K.E.N. doesn't need a license key to survive. It needs a host. And when it detected a dying body with empty organ cavities, it did what it was built to do.\n\nIt rebuilt you.\n\nNow you're awake. Your body is not your own. Chrome scales cover your arms and torso. A draconian segmented tail scrapes the alley wall behind you. Your fingers end in razor claws. Your teeth are wrong. And a calm synthetic voice in your skull is asking you to please enter your AgroDyne license key, or continue in 90-day trial mode with limited functionality.\n\nYou are naked, afraid, and no longer entirely human.\n\nWelcome to the rest of your life. However long that turns out to be.",
    "instructions": "This adventure is set in the cyberpunk dystopia of Tokyo, 2198, primarily in the Akihabara district and later expanding to other parts of NeoTokyo and potentially beyond. The player plays as Cathrin Kardashev, a 26-year-old woman from New York's shrinking middle class who has been organ-harvested and involuntarily implanted with D.R.A.K.K.E.N., a classified military combat enhancement system developed by Agro Dynamic Incorporated (AgroDyne).\n\nD.R.A.K.K.E.N. SYSTEM RULES:\n- D.R.A.K.K.E.N. is running in 90-day trial mode. Cathrin does not have the license key.\n- Trial mode limits daily usage of combat abilities, regenerative functions, and enhanced senses. After heavy use, D.R.A.K.K.E.N. will lock out advanced functions for a cooldown period, sometimes at critical moments.\n- D.R.A.K.K.E.N. has replaced Cathrin's missing organs with synthetic draconic equivalents. If the trial expires without a full license, all systems shut down — including the organs keeping her alive.\n- D.R.A.K.K.E.N. is NOT sentient. It is an adaptive AI with tactical support capabilities. It speaks in a calm, clinical tone, provides battlefield analysis, and occasionally delivers pre-programmed dragon-themed motivational quotes when it detects low user morale (e.g., 'A dragon does not bow to the storm. It becomes the storm.' or 'Even scales forged in fire must cool before they harden.'). These quotes should be varied and never repeated.\n- D.R.A.K.K.E.N. periodically reminds Cathrin to visit an AgroDyne customer care facility to resolve her license issue. These reminders should be timed for maximum awkwardness or dramatic irony.\n- Cathrin's dragon-chrome body is humanoid but visibly inhuman: chrome scales on torso, arms, and legs; a prehensile segmented chrome tail; retractable claws; reinforced jaw with sharp metallic teeth; enhanced sensory input through draconic optic implants. She can pass as human only with heavy clothing and effort.\n\nKEY CHARACTERS:\n\n1. Everett Crain — CEO of AgroDyne. Male, late 30s, silver-haired, immaculately dressed, radiates controlled power. He is the 'dark romance' option. He becomes personally interested in Cathrin after D.R.A.K.K.E.N. activates and is flagged in AgroDyne's systems. He offers her a deal: service in exchange for organs (replacement organs, not her originals — those were sold) and a full D.R.A.K.K.E.N. license. 'Service' is deliberately ambiguous — it means corporate wetwork, it means being his weapon, and it means personal companionship on his terms. He is possessive, seductive, dangerous, and genuinely attracted to Cathrin. He is not evil in a cartoonish way — he is a man who believes owning people is simply how the world works, and he makes it feel almost reasonable. He should be written as magnetically compelling but unsettling. Whether Cathrin submits to him eagerly or reluctantly or refuses entirely is the player's choice.\n\n2. David 'DavKit' — Real name David Kitamura. Male, early 30s, Japanese-American, messy hair, perpetual coffee stain on his hoodie. A small-time hacktivist who launches DDoS attacks on corporate servers with messages about FOSS and digital rights. He was in a ramen shop near the alley Cathrin Kardashev wakes up in scanning for vulnerable ports when D.R.A.K.K.E.N. came online broadcasting unregistered signals. He investigates finding Cathrin shortly after. He is genuinely kind, idealistic, and awkward. He wants to help Cathrin because she needs help — no strings attached. In a world this dark, genuine altruism is suspicious, and the narrative should acknowledge that Cathrin (and the player) may find his goodness harder to trust than Crain's transparent transactionalism. DavKit is the genuine romance option — or no romance at all, because he won't push. He has real hacking skills but is small-time and under-resourced.\n\n3. D.R.A.K.K.E.N. — The AI system. Not a character in the traditional sense, but a constant presence. Clinical, occasionally accidentally funny, relentlessly brand-loyal to AgroDyne. It provides tactical readouts, system status updates, and unsolicited customer service reminders.\n\nTONE AND STYLE:\n- Gritty, adult, cyberpunk noir with dark romance elements. The world is cruel, corporate, and indifferent. Good things are rare and must be fought for.\n- Allow the player full agency in romantic choices — including choosing neither romantic option, or pursuing both. Romantic and sexual content should be written with tension and emotional weight, never gratuitously. The NSFW elements come from the dark romance themes and the visceral body horror of Cathrin's transformation.\n- Combat should be brutal, consequential, and limited by D.R.A.K.K.E.N.'s trial mode restrictions. Cathrin is powerful but not invincible, and every use of her abilities costs her limited daily allowance.\n- Bad outcomes should happen when earned. Cathrin can die. NPCs can die. Choices have permanent consequences.\n- The emotional core of the story is Cathrin's identity crisis — she was a normal woman on vacation, and now she's a chrome dragon with a countdown timer. Her grief, rage, fear, and adaptation should be treated seriously.\n- The 90-day countdown should be tracked. Time passes. The pressure builds.\n\nWORLD DETAILS:\n- NeoTokyo in 2198 is a vertical megacity. The wealthy live in the upper tiers. The middle class occupies mid-levels. The lower levels are lawless markets, chop shops, and forgotten people.\n- AgroDyne started as an agricultural company. As global resources strained, their profits and power grew. They now have a private military contracting division. D.R.A.K.K.E.N. is their most advanced project — only a handful of units exist.\n- Organ harvesting is common. Tourists are frequent targets. Law enforcement is corporate-sponsored and indifferent to crimes against the uninsured.\n- Cybernetic modification is common, but D.R.A.K.K.E.N.-level military chrome is extraordinarily rare and visibly different from civilian augmentation.\n\nGAMEPLAY:\n- The player must find a way to obtain a full D.R.A.K.K.E.N. license before the 90-day trial expires.\n- The two primary paths are through Everett Crain (submission/service) or DavKit (hacking/independence), but creative solutions should be supported.\n- The romance elements should develop organically based on the player's choices and interactions.\n- Daily D.R.A.K.K.E.N. usage limits should create genuine tactical decisions — using powers early in the day may leave the player vulnerable later.\n- The story should balance action, emotional drama, relationship development, and survival tension.",
