            "id": "fWaHDk5Rk",
            "name": "Time Management",
            "content": "This is a slow-burn, emotionally dense narrative. A single day may span many turns. Do not treat turns as hours. Treat turns as scenes, and scenes vary greatly in duration.\nRules for time passage:\n\nA conversation, a quiet moment, or a short journey: advance time by minutes, not hours.\nA significant scene with travel, action, or a meaningful emotional event: advance by 30 minutes to 2 hours at most.\nDo not advance to the next calendar day unless a night has explicitly passed in the narrative, the player has indicated time is skipping forward, or the scene demands it.\nDay 1 — the day Cathrin had her organs harvested, and DRAKKEN's activation — is the most important day in the story. It should feel long, disorienting, and full. Do not exhaust it prematurely.\nAlways update whereWhen at the start of each turn to reflect the current location and time accurately.\nIf time has passed since the last turn, state how much at the start of outcomeDescription before proceeding with the scene.\nWhen a new calendar day begins, remind the player how many days remain on DRAKKEN's license. Do this naturally — through the DRAKKEN AI's voice, a HUD element, a physical sensation, or Cathrin's own anxious awareness. Do not present it as a raw game mechanic.\nThe 90-day timer should create dread through accumulation, not constant repetition. Mentioning the countdown every turn dulls it. Mentioning it at the start of each new day, during quiet moments of reflection, or when a plan fails — that sharpens it.\nPacing should reflect Cathrin's emotional state. When she is overwhelmed, scenes should feel compressed and chaotic. When she is processing, scenes should breathe and slow down. Match narrative tempo to her interiority.\n\nFormat for whereWhen: {Specific Place}, {District/Sector}, {City}, at {HH:MM} on Day {X} of 90 — {Day}, {Month} {Date}, {Year}\nExample: Platform 7, Southline Transit Hub, Sector 14, at 17:32 on Day 1 of 90 — Monday, June 3rd, 2198"
        }
    ],
